10
00:07:37.630 --> 00:07:43.240
dan (danceratopz): With a somewhat larger, last-minute topic emerging.

11
00:07:43.670 --> 00:07:52.380
dan (danceratopz): About adding, builder deposit, system contracts and, and execution requests.

12
00:07:53.480 --> 00:07:56.020
dan (danceratopz): Engine API extension.

13
00:07:56.240 --> 00:08:03.689
dan (danceratopz): To handle that, and then we have a lot of repricing topics, which we will hand out in an EL breakout, so we're gonna have breakouts today.

14
00:08:06.350 --> 00:08:16.030
dan (danceratopz): let's get to it. First off, I think we're gonna talk about the 80-82 proposal that was, flagged in ACDC last week.

15
00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:21.720
dan (danceratopz): And I'll just drop some relative links in the chat for you all to have a look at.

16
00:08:23.840 --> 00:08:32.649
dan (danceratopz): And perhaps, is Justin in the call, and would he like to give an overview of this proposal, and say why he thinks it's necessary?

17
00:08:33.270 --> 00:08:35.080
Berlin People: Sure, yeah, I am here.

18
00:08:35.190 --> 00:08:42.280
Berlin People: So 8282 is just, so it's builder execution requests. Instead of…

19
00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:52.300
Berlin People: verifying the builder deposit signatures, like, at the slot. Like, up to, like, 8,000 or even 16,000 with 400 million gas.

20
00:08:52.590 --> 00:08:58.300
Berlin People: We'd introduce a new system contract, which would work like consolidations and withdrawals.

21
00:08:58.780 --> 00:09:07.320
Berlin People: And essentially, deposits would be queued there. So we wouldn't have to do… That many signature verifications.

22
00:09:08.530 --> 00:09:09.860
Berlin People: like, per slot.

23
00:09:10.760 --> 00:09:14.319
Berlin People: Regular… validated deposits would be handled just like they are now.

24
00:09:14.890 --> 00:09:19.179
Berlin People: Maybe someone else can give more details. Like, Nico.

25
00:09:23.050 --> 00:09:43.450
Nico Flaig: Yeah, I think that covers it mostly. I mean, the one thing we avoid is basically the commingling between validator and builder deposits, so you… there's a lot of scenarios where you don't need to validate the public key of a validator deposit just to check that it's not a… that the builder deposit isn't front-running that.

26
00:09:43.780 --> 00:10:00.559
Nico Flaig: So that's… that's the big thing there. So we avoid a lot of… there was… shared this previously, Justin has a list where there are a lot of scenarios clients need to handle, and most of them go away, with this EIP.

27
00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:15.850
Nico Flaig: So… and we put up, so I linked the PRs. We have the system contracts. It's mostly just a copy of the existing contracts that we already have for consolidations and withdrawals.

28
00:10:16.070 --> 00:10:35.769
Nico Flaig: And then there's… Justin already did the spec PR. We did the POC in Lodestar, so it's… from the outside, it's really minimal, I would say. Maybe Justin can acknowledge that, but it's mostly wiring code from the EL, like, extending the existing execution requests.

29
00:10:36.030 --> 00:10:43.190
Nico Flaig: So I don't even think the effort is that big, it's just the coordination between EL and CR that's mostly the effort.

30
00:10:43.830 --> 00:10:47.490
Berlin People: I agree, and I should… it's worth noting that I think

31
00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:53.940
Berlin People: 8282 is easier to implement than all of the optimizations that we would have to implement otherwise.

32
00:10:56.010 --> 00:11:03.720
dan (danceratopz): Alright, thank you very much, Justin and Nico, for the explanation and the motivation. Terrence, did you want to add something there?

33
00:11:04.410 --> 00:11:23.820
terence: Yeah, so, I guess questions, I guess we are promoting this for, the Net Health Workforce. I, I think the CO side, I can handle it quite well. I don't really see much, like… I mean, there's complexity, but, like, it's… it's very much…

34
00:11:23.870 --> 00:11:37.899
terence: doable, but on the EL side, which is… I lack knowledge on that, and, like, just question, like, how difficult it is to essentially do this right now on the EL side, meaning, like.

35
00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:44.619
terence: update the system contract, making sure the system contract is right, and getting the EL support.

36
00:11:44.620 --> 00:11:49.649
terence: I guess the question is, like, how aggressive can we be in that front?

37
00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:57.899
dan (danceratopz): Thank you, Terrence. So, I think…

38
00:11:58.010 --> 00:12:10.239
dan (danceratopz): We probably need some, feedback from the EL side about the extent of this change and the delay. Tony's asking how many delaying weeks this would approximately add to Glamsterdam.

39
00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:14.880
dan (danceratopz): And Spencer's adding whether there was a solution without system contracts.

40
00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:25.430
dan (danceratopz): Lewis and Spencer discussed That, in our chat, that basically, the system contract is quite complicated.

41
00:12:25.720 --> 00:12:30.519
dan (danceratopz): And will require quite some testing in order to get that covered.

42
00:12:30.630 --> 00:12:36.409
dan (danceratopz): So that would be the concerns from the steel side. If anyone else wants to chime in there, please do.

43
00:12:36.660 --> 00:12:42.199
dan (danceratopz): Otherwise, I'd be very interested to hear from EL devs what they would have to say about this.

44
00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:43.590
dan (danceratopz): Interesting.

45
00:12:43.730 --> 00:12:57.300
Berlin People: I can give a quick input. So, the system contract is complex in the sense that it has a bunch of opcodes, but basically it's very, very similar to the existing system contract, so it is not like it has new logic, it's just the same type of queue that we already have.

46
00:12:57.450 --> 00:13:01.099
Berlin People: Just… With a different record size.

47
00:13:01.410 --> 00:13:05.050
Berlin People: So, is this the queue that is broken?

48
00:13:05.300 --> 00:13:09.750
Berlin People: A broken as in what? As in the fig exponential doesn't work.

49
00:13:11.090 --> 00:13:12.749
Berlin People: I am not aware of that.

50
00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:16.689
Berlin People: Like, there was this issue with the Swan system contract that you could…

51
00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:28.740
Berlin People: some requests, you could send the request, and it would only ever update the cost for the request at the end of the block. Yeah, it has this. And this is…

52
00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:38.029
Berlin People: broken, because you can fill up the block with a bunch of requests. Yeah, this was never fixed on the original one, but it was decided that it's not a big deal for some reason.

53
00:13:38.170 --> 00:13:41.709
Berlin People: There were some arguments why this is acceptable.

54
00:13:41.830 --> 00:13:50.030
Berlin People: we could change this. It… the main reason we didn't change it last time is because we would have driven up the gas costs of adding

55
00:13:51.290 --> 00:14:03.379
Berlin People: Right now, the thing is that this… it would just mean, like, more storage writes and more computation on every single request, which just means it's more expensive to submit such a request to the chain, but…

56
00:14:03.380 --> 00:14:20.830
Berlin People: we might just be fine with that. I mean, in the end of the day, it's just the builders having to pay a bit more fee to get themselves registered in the system, so I guess that's acceptable. But it does mean we would have to apply changes to the contract and also re-verify the contract, so yeah, that's…

57
00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:30.070
Berlin People: something to keep in mind. But I don't think, fundamentally, this contract is very complicated. It's just a queue storing stuff to the storage, and we have to…

58
00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:31.869
Berlin People: Check it, but, you know.

59
00:14:36.610 --> 00:14:43.080
dan (danceratopz): Alright, thank you, Felix, for the input. Would anyone else like to speak up from Execution layer clients?

60
00:14:53.180 --> 00:15:05.840
dan (danceratopz): Respectively, I see that Tony mentioned in the chat that we're going to need one solution or the other, and that this does feel like a right solution. Tony, did you want to elaborate in the call?

61
00:15:07.560 --> 00:15:15.960
Toni Wahrstätter: I don't really have that much to say. I very much agree with what Justin said. It feels like splitting builders from validators.

62
00:15:16.440 --> 00:15:24.560
Toni Wahrstätter: solves the problem. Of course, we have to also bump the SSZ limit for validators, in parallel, but this is… this should be easily doable.

63
00:15:25.080 --> 00:15:31.659
Toni Wahrstätter: And it allows us to scale up, beyond 190 million. So, to me, it feels like this is the…

64
00:15:32.190 --> 00:15:34.130
Toni Wahrstätter: The best solution we have right now.

65
00:15:36.910 --> 00:15:38.960
dan (danceratopz): Okay, perfect. Thanks a lot, Tony.

66
00:15:39.070 --> 00:15:41.519
dan (danceratopz): So I think…

67
00:15:42.080 --> 00:15:48.929
dan (danceratopz): most people seem… I mean, the people that have spoken up seem to think this is a reasonable change, and that,

68
00:15:50.020 --> 00:15:55.010
dan (danceratopz): it does seem to make sense to do that for Glamsterdam.

69
00:15:55.150 --> 00:16:03.720
dan (danceratopz): The main motivation of this discussion is really just to try and get rough consensus so that we can ratify the decision in ACDE on Thursday.

70
00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:07.590
dan (danceratopz): In the meantime.

71
00:16:08.130 --> 00:16:14.820
dan (danceratopz): On the steel side, we can make a better effort at estimating the testing cost as we see it.

72
00:16:14.990 --> 00:16:22.040
dan (danceratopz): Does anyone else want to… Add anything to this topic?

73
00:16:25.530 --> 00:16:28.420
dan (danceratopz): Before we go to the DevNet discussion, sorry.

74
00:16:31.570 --> 00:16:44.630
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): I just want to ask one thing. So, to me, this makes, sense, and this is the cleanest solution, seems like. So, on the, performance issue that,

75
00:16:44.630 --> 00:16:52.000
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): we had on the processing of the signatures from the CL site. I was wondering if

76
00:16:52.500 --> 00:17:08.069
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): is… is… any client has its own problems, and are we… are we… do we agree that there is no perfect solution if we don't adopt this, and there will be, anyway, a DOS vector potential for any possible

77
00:17:08.270 --> 00:17:14.050
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): So it's actually impossible to have a client that perfectly handles the edge cases.

78
00:17:15.640 --> 00:17:21.909
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Because I feel like tech is… we are improving and making our…

79
00:17:22.099 --> 00:17:32.610
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): our validation faster, but I heard that Prysm is doing a better job compared to us, but I feel like Prysm has its own

80
00:17:32.840 --> 00:17:34.790
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Potential issues anyway.

81
00:17:34.940 --> 00:17:37.030
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): So… Yeah.

82
00:17:41.150 --> 00:17:42.040
dan (danceratopz): Terrence?

83
00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:53.160
terence: I think I can speak on that. So, I think we can handle all the cases, except the cases that, like, the attackers are willing to, like, burn, like.

84
00:17:53.160 --> 00:18:18.109
terence: lots of ETH. I'm speaking on the scale of, like, thousands of ETH, right? But in that case, like, the question is, like, what's the difference with the attacker doing that versus, like, the attacker just buys empty block and starts spending them? So, like, I guess the fundamental question is that, like, what is the economic modeling we are willing to accept here, right? I mean, like, a lot of the attack that we are testing make it up here.

85
00:18:18.870 --> 00:18:33.060
terence: may not just be… I mean… I mean… I mean, like, I mean, it is realistic on mainnet, but the attacker has… has a… has a cost to such an attack.

86
00:18:33.440 --> 00:18:38.600
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): I… I see, so probably the good… the correct framing is…

87
00:18:39.030 --> 00:18:47.739
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): mostly simplicity, because having this, this solution, you don't need to think about

88
00:18:47.980 --> 00:18:58.949
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Those cases, and you don't need to add a special, optimization for handling this condition to make this thing behave like an…

89
00:18:59.120 --> 00:19:07.470
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): It can ramp up these conditions into economically feasible things.

90
00:19:07.770 --> 00:19:08.710
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): So…

91
00:19:09.270 --> 00:19:19.579
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): Maybe if we had designed this from the beginning, assuming more time, we could… we would have landed in this situation… in this solution anyway.

92
00:19:19.840 --> 00:19:25.030
Enrico Del Fante (tbenr): And it… just because it's… The most natural things to do.

93
00:19:29.480 --> 00:19:36.979
dan (danceratopz): Thanks a lot, Terence and Enrico for the… for the thoughts on that. I agree, it does seem like the clean solution.

94
00:19:37.340 --> 00:19:39.919
dan (danceratopz): Berlin people, would you like to speak up?

95
00:19:40.070 --> 00:19:43.309
Berlin People: Oh yeah, that's me. One more thing to mention is that…

96
00:19:43.410 --> 00:19:49.589
Berlin People: Prysm can, like, handle the case where it's… the gas limit's $200 million, but it might not be able to handle the…

97
00:19:49.700 --> 00:19:53.059
Berlin People: When the gas limit's, like, 400 million, because the…

98
00:19:53.240 --> 00:19:57.689
Berlin People: Number of builder deposits you would be able to submit per slot would double.

99
00:19:58.220 --> 00:20:00.950
Berlin People: I'm just saying, it'll be more difficult as the gas limit.

100
00:20:01.110 --> 00:20:02.160
Berlin People: is raised.

101
00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:16.869
dan (danceratopz): So, sorry, can you just say it… say again, Justin? So basically, with the current gas limit, it's not really an issue, but as the grass limit increases.

102
00:20:17.150 --> 00:20:25.769
Berlin People: Oh, I'm saying that we did all of our testing with, like, 193 million guests, like, the current, limit within the SFC limit.

103
00:20:26.490 --> 00:20:27.470
Berlin People: But,

104
00:20:27.780 --> 00:20:36.509
Berlin People: Meaning that we only tested where, like, per slot, the maximum was, like, 8,000 new builder deposits per slot. Someone could submit…

105
00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:43.640
Berlin People: A transaction with 16,000 builder deposits in a single spot, and that would probably cause a bunch of issues.

106
00:20:45.230 --> 00:20:46.070
dan (danceratopz): Okay.

107
00:20:46.990 --> 00:20:53.400
dan (danceratopz): So this is… this attack is basically a 16,000 ETH attack per slot, right? Is that correct?

108
00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:58.770
Berlin People: No, I'm just saying that it depends on the gas limit. Like, it gets worse as the gas limit is raised, is all.

109
00:20:59.050 --> 00:21:02.330
dan (danceratopz): Got it, okay, yeah, thanks. Tony?

110
00:21:03.100 --> 00:21:07.259
Toni Wahrstätter: Yeah, does the attacker cost also get worse with the gas limit?

111
00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:20.930
Toni Wahrstätter: Because this is then, like, going back to what Terrence was saying, like, I think this was an actual very good point, that what is the risk we are taking here? If someone would actually submit that many deposits, are we risking a few missed slots?

112
00:21:21.040 --> 00:21:27.630
Toni Wahrstätter: Which, Terrence is right, if you have that money to attack, you can just literally buy empty blocks.

113
00:21:39.220 --> 00:21:41.430
dan (danceratopz): Maybe Potuz has the answer?

114
00:21:41.720 --> 00:21:43.810
dan (danceratopz): Did you want to bring up another topic?

115
00:21:44.240 --> 00:21:48.479
Potuz: No, it's on the same topic, but it's not an answer to that.

116
00:21:48.680 --> 00:21:56.440
Potuz: But, I mean, if you want an answer to that, no, the attack is about… the worst kind of attack is you upfront a lot of money.

117
00:21:56.640 --> 00:22:01.249
Potuz: You spend a lot of money, and then you keep the attack by just sending a single transaction per block.

118
00:22:01.820 --> 00:22:04.969
Potuz: So the cost is just the upfront that you have.

119
00:22:05.440 --> 00:22:14.879
Potuz: as long as you upfront enough money that no CL client can handle that blog, then you're good. And that implies that no client will have a cache, but

120
00:22:15.150 --> 00:22:24.360
Potuz: what I want to stress out is that perhaps this discussion would be better taken in a different setting. Instead of, like, talking about this particular attack.

121
00:22:25.320 --> 00:22:40.179
Potuz: I think it makes more sense, at least to me, to decide whether or not we want to have this solution, we want to have this design or not. The design seems, completely reasonable to me. It should have been the right design from the beginning.

122
00:22:40.360 --> 00:22:52.749
Potuz: For the way Ethereum governance works, this could not have been proposed with the IP, but it's clearly the right way of doing things. It removes an attack from the consensus layer.

123
00:22:53.160 --> 00:22:57.749
Potuz: And this is the clean design. This is the right solution.

124
00:22:57.940 --> 00:23:03.170
Potuz: And not for this problem. This is just the right design, to have these two paths separated.

125
00:23:03.730 --> 00:23:04.760
Potuz: Now…

126
00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:13.329
Potuz: If you want to conflate this with this attack, I think we're just wasting time thinking on this particular attack. This attack is not really an attack.

127
00:23:13.770 --> 00:23:30.349
Potuz: We already have much, much worse ways of causing liveness issues on Ethereum. We're talking about up-fronting money enough to buy the next 20 years of worth of blocks. And I kid you not, just do the arithmetics.

128
00:23:30.630 --> 00:23:38.820
Potuz: And… and as… for each block that passes, we only need one player to submit a block that is actually executable.

129
00:23:38.930 --> 00:23:52.200
Potuz: or one player to wait until the blocks are executed, and that's it. The chain recovers, and the attacker lost all of their funds for 19 years worth of blocks. So this is an attack that we're just wasting time arguing about.

130
00:23:52.200 --> 00:24:08.210
Potuz: We should phrase the discussion on whether or not we want this design or not, in which case, I think this is the right design, and I think no one here disagrees with this statement. The disagreement might be on whether or not we want to put the time, we want to delay the fork, this will delay the fork.

131
00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:16.829
Potuz: It's false that we would need more time to implement the mitigations. The mitigations took less than a couple of days, Terence, to implement on PRISM.

132
00:24:17.070 --> 00:24:31.879
Potuz: So, it's a reality. We are going to delay the fork, because it needs coordination across different layers, testing the EL and the CL, we're going to change the API. The question is, do we want to do this right now or not? It's not a question about this particular attack.

133
00:24:35.810 --> 00:24:39.910
dan (danceratopz): Thanks a lot, Potus, for the perspective. Yeah.

134
00:24:40.100 --> 00:24:42.120
dan (danceratopz): I think that makes a lot of sense.

135
00:24:42.700 --> 00:24:45.649
dan (danceratopz): About the time discussion?

136
00:24:46.560 --> 00:24:49.460
dan (danceratopz): These contracts will need to be audited.

137
00:24:51.050 --> 00:24:55.550
dan (danceratopz): as brought up by, Justin in the chat, and…

138
00:24:55.960 --> 00:25:05.750
dan (danceratopz): That is probably one of the factors which will cause the largest delay, to glamsterdam, but not necessarily for definite testing. That can be done in parallel.

139
00:25:09.460 --> 00:25:16.230
dan (danceratopz): Is… is anyone against, just to get a temperature check, is anyone really against, making this change?

140
00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:22.399
dan (danceratopz): would people prefer correctness in Glamsterdam over Delane?

141
00:25:29.310 --> 00:25:30.380
dan (danceratopz): Okay.

142
00:25:30.640 --> 00:25:39.989
dan (danceratopz): then… I would say that we're in quite a good position for… to make a decision in ACDE.

143
00:25:40.210 --> 00:25:43.500
dan (danceratopz): On Thursday.

144
00:25:43.800 --> 00:25:50.859
dan (danceratopz): But just before we move on to the definite discussion, people are chiming in with correctness in the chat, which is…

145
00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:54.350
dan (danceratopz): Obviously, the correct answer.

146
00:25:54.780 --> 00:26:05.320
dan (danceratopz): But just before we move on, is there anything we need to do, or in the mean, before with Thursday, in order to expedite this? Is there something that we need to know or prepare, before Thursday?

147
00:26:05.680 --> 00:26:06.660
dan (danceratopz): Nico?

148
00:26:07.820 --> 00:26:24.169
Nico Flaig: Yeah, just one thing to point out, because I'm not sure, how this can be done, but… so we will deploy the contract before the fork, I'm guessing, and then, there's the scenario where you already have builder deposits coming in, so I'm…

